### Declaring a React Plugin as an Extension Decorator (JavaScript)

Source: https://lexical.dev/docs/extensions/react

Demonstrates how to wrap a legacy React Lexical plugin into an extension that leverages ReactExtension's decorator capabilities. This allows the plugin to be managed and rendered automatically by the Lexical system.

```javascript
// This is exactly how you would write a legacy React plug-in
function LogEditorPlugin() {
 const [editor] = useLexicalComposerContext()
 useEffect(() => {
   console.log(editor);
 }, [editor]);
 return null;
}
// This is how you would declare the plugin as an extension
// that depends on React and renders this plug-in as a decorator
export const LogEditorExtension = defineExtension({
 name: "@example/LogEditor",
 dependencies: [
   configExtension(ReactExtension, {
     decorators: [<LogEditorPlugin />]
   }),
 ],
});

```

